        "content": "<p>Hi! <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"499481\">@Mateo Torres-Ruiz</span> , Alexandra Silva, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"351836\">@Fabio Zanasi</span> , and I have just uploaded <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.14701\">an arXiv preprint</a> which might be of interest to subscribers of this stream, in particular to those who care about axiomatising probability theory in Markov categories (though it is written mainly for a programming language theory audience).</p>\n<p>One of our main results is a presentation, using generators and equations, of the Markov category of stochastic maps between objects that are powers of the two-element set, with the cartesian product as monoidal product. We give this presentation using string diagrams: these can be thought of as <em>probabilistic circuits</em>, i.e., Boolean circuits with additional primitives for coin flips (Bernoulli distributions) and explicit conditioning. Conditioning-free circuits correspond to those circuits that can be discarded (we call them causal circuits) and their semantics lands in FinStoch. Another way to formulate what I said above is that causal circuits modulo the equational theory we give in the paper are equivalent to the full monoidal subcategory of (FinStoch,<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span>) on powers of the Booleans. This means that any two circuits that denote the same stochastic map can be shown to be equal using only equational reasoning.</p>\n<p>Circuits that include conditioning operations may contain unsatisfiable conditions however (this is the usual problem with conditioning on events of measure zero), and thus require a more sophisticated semantics. There are several ways of dealing with this issue in the literature on probabilistic programming: in this paper, we chose to interpret circuits with conditioning in a category of sub-stochastic maps (the distributions involved sum to at most 1), quotiented by the equivalence relation that identifies them whenever they are proportional (this was first proposed as categorical semantics in the work of Dario Stein and Sam Staton afaik). Our second main result is a presentation of this monoidal category, once again on objects that are powers of the Booleans. Interestingly, it is not Markov, since not all its morphisms are causal (conditioning is not, for example), but it is compact-closed. In fact, it is a hypergraph category with copy, delete, conditioning, and the uniform distribution giving the required Frobenius algebra on the Booleans.</p>",
        "id": 465655181,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724827652
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is cool!</p>\n<p>Do you know if the subcategory of spans of finite sets whose objects are powers of 2 embed within this category of sub-stochastic maps?  I am curious, because I am interested in how nondeterminism and probability can be made to interact.</p>",
        "id": 465791799,
        "sender_full_name": "Cole Comfort",
        "timestamp": 1724857092
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hmm... spans of finite sets correspond to matrices whose entries are natural numbers, so perhaps you could map such a matrix <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> to (the equivalence class) of the substochastic map/matrix whose columns are the re-normalised columns of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> (and the same column when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> has an all-zeroes column). This will not give you a faithful functor though, if it even gives you a functor at all.</p>",
        "id": 465795580,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724858134
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm also not sure why an embedding of spans would count as combining nondeterminism and probability in your opinion. The classic issue with combining these two effects this is that there is no distributive law between the powerset monad and the distribution monad. However, there are alternatives, like the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/convex+powerset+of+distributions+monad\">convex powerset monad</a> which can be seen to combine them in a more limited sense. Is that the sort of thing you're looking for? Alternatively, the multiset monad does distribute over the distribution monad, iirc, and the Kleisli category of the multiset monad is equivalent to the category of spans of finite sets (with finite apex as well), so you might want to look into that instead.</p>",
        "id": 465913172,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724910566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yet another approach is the one proposed by <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"309295\">@Dario Stein</span> and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"426789\">@Richard Samuelson</span> in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.14024\">A Category for unifying Gaussian Probability and Nondeterminism</a>. They define an <em>extended Gaussian</em> over some vector space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> as a Gaussian distribution on a quotient space of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V/D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>, where the subspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> can be thought of as a \"nondeterministic fiber\". (And, as you know, we've axiomatised this category and more in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.02284\">Graphical Quadratic Algebra</a>). </p>\n<p>The same idea could perhaps be applied in the discrete setting? We could define an extended distribution over some (finite) set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a pair of an equivalence relation over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and a distribution over its equivalence classes.</p>",
        "id": 465915170,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724911634
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I'm not sure how to extend this idea to define a category of extended stochastic maps. If we follow the idea of the paper above, we should define an extended stochastic map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\rightarrow Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> as a triple <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>∼</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>f</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\sim, f,\\phi)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of an equivalence relation over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo>∼</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f:X\\rightarrow Y/\\sim</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span></span></span>, and a probability distribution over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo>∼</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y/\\sim</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span></span></span>. However, with this definition we do not recover stochastic maps as a special case, since we do not have a distribution for each element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. The alternative would be to define extended stochastic maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> as <em>stochastic</em> maps of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo>∼</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\rightarrow Y/\\sim</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span></span></span>, but I don't know how to compose these.</p>",
        "id": 465919827,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724913113
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277342\">Robin Piedeleu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/253118-theory.3A-categorical-probability/topic/Axiomatisation.20of.20probabilistic.20Boolean.20circuits/near/465915170\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yet another approach is the one proposed by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"309295\">Dario Stein</span> and <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"426789\">Richard Samuelson</span> in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.14024\">A Category for unifying Gaussian Probability and Nondeterminism</a>. They define an <em>extended Gaussian</em> over some vector space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> as a Gaussian distribution on a quotient space of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V/D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>, where the subspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> can be thought of as a \"nondeterministic fiber\". (And, as you know, we've axiomatised this category and more in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.02284\">Graphical Quadratic Algebra</a>). </p>\n<p>The same idea could perhaps be applied in the discrete setting? We could define an extended distribution over some (finite) set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a pair of an equivalence relation over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and a distribution over its equivalence classes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277342\">@Robin Piedeleu</span> , this is indeed an intriguing and natural idea and I've tried to make it work. Here's the story: We can focus on a simpler setup, namely pure nondeterminism without probability in <strong>Set</strong>. A map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> shall be a pair <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>f</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>∼</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(f,\\sim)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">∼</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : X \\to Y/{\\sim}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span></span></span></span>. I called this a \"copartial map\" because a map into a quotient is somehow dual to a partial map (a map out of a subobject). This forms a category (composition by pushout), however it fails to be monoidal (or Markov) in the way you want it to be. If your monoidal structure is coproduct <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span> then everything works fine (like in general categories of decorated cospans). However, to compare this with probability theory, you really want the cartesian product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span>, because that's how you talk about joint distributions, and it's what <strong>FinStoch</strong> formalizes. It turns out <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span> does not give a valid monoidal structure on copartial maps, essentially because the relevant class of pushouts (one leg epi) does <strong>not</strong> commute with products. It <em>does</em> in vector spaces, which is what makes extended Gaussians work, but vector spaces have biproducts so you can't tell the difference between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 465921818,
        "sender_full_name": "Dario Stein",
        "timestamp": 1724914037
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My guess is that the semantic issue here (about “a distribution over a partition” not being a kind of epistemic state that is compatible with ×) can be illustrated as follows. Suppose I have the state of knowledge ((x≤1, x&gt;1), (0.6, 0.4)) about x, and the state of knowledge ((y≤2, y&gt;2), (0.7, 0.3)) about y. Then, my state of knowledge about (x,y) can <em>not</em> be expressed as ((x≤1∧y≤2, x≤1∧y&gt;2, x&gt;1∧y≤2, x&gt;1∧y&gt;2), (p₀₀,p₀₁,p₁₀,p₁₁)), because I don’t know whether x and y are independent, or how they might be dependent.</p>",
        "id": 465973579,
        "sender_full_name": "davidad (David Dalrymple)",
        "timestamp": 1724928187
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My current guess of the most promising “epistemic state” is</p>\n<ul>\n<li>instead of a partition, or even a list of predicates, a list of (well-behaved) [0,∞]-valued functions</li>\n<li>instead of a distribution, or even a list of expected values, a list of known <em>upper bounds</em> on expected values.<br>\nThis idea is based on <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.17127\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.17127</a></li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 465974890,
        "sender_full_name": "davidad (David Dalrymple)",
        "timestamp": 1724928511
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"309295\">Dario Stein</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/253118-theory.3A-categorical-probability/topic/Axiomatisation.20of.20probabilistic.20Boolean.20circuits/near/465921818\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277342\">Robin Piedeleu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/253118-theory.3A-categorical-probability/topic/Axiomatisation.20of.20probabilistic.20Boolean.20circuits/near/465915170\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yet another approach is the one proposed by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"309295\">Dario Stein</span> and <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"426789\">Richard Samuelson</span> in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.14024\">A Category for unifying Gaussian Probability and Nondeterminism</a>. They define an <em>extended Gaussian</em> over some vector space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> as a Gaussian distribution on a quotient space of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V/D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>, where the subspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> can be thought of as a \"nondeterministic fiber\". (And, as you know, we've axiomatised this category and more in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.02284\">Graphical Quadratic Algebra</a>). </p>\n<p>The same idea could perhaps be applied in the discrete setting? We could define an extended distribution over some (finite) set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a pair of an equivalence relation over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and a distribution over its equivalence classes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277342\">Robin Piedeleu</span> , this is indeed an intriguing and natural idea and I've tried to make it work. Here's the story: We can focus on a simpler setup, namely pure nondeterminism without probability in <strong>Set</strong>. A map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> shall be a pair <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>f</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>∼</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(f,\\sim)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">∼</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : X \\to Y/{\\sim}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span></span></span></span></span>. I called this a \"copartial map\" because a map into a quotient is somehow dual to a partial map (a map out of a subobject). This forms a category (composition by pushout), however it fails to be monoidal (or Markov) in the way you want it to be. If your monoidal structure is coproduct <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span> then everything works fine (like in general categories of decorated cospans). However, to compare this with probability theory, you really want the cartesian product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span>, because that's how you talk about joint distributions, and it's what <strong>FinStoch</strong> formalizes. It turns out <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span> does not give a valid monoidal structure on copartial maps, essentially because the relevant class of pushouts (one leg epi) does <strong>not</strong> commute with products. It <em>does</em> in vector spaces, which is what makes extended Gaussians work, but vector spaces have biproducts so you can't tell the difference between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>What kind of quotient is this that gives you such a copartial map?</p>",
        "id": 465985587,
        "sender_full_name": "Cole Comfort",
        "timestamp": 1724930908
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think Dario just means a quotient given by an equivalence relation over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>. And the equivalence relation is part of the data of such a map.</p>",
        "id": 465985949,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724931012
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282874\">davidad (David Dalrymple)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/253118-theory.3A-categorical-probability/topic/Axiomatisation.20of.20probabilistic.20Boolean.20circuits/near/465974890\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>My current guess of the most promising “epistemic state” is</p>\n<ul>\n<li>instead of a partition, or even a list of predicates, a list of (well-behaved) [0,∞]-valued functions</li>\n<li>instead of a distribution, or even a list of expected values, a list of known <em>upper bounds</em> on expected values.<br>\nThis idea is based on <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.17127\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.17127</a></li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This looks interesting, but replacing partitions by [0,∞]-valued functions kind of defeats the purpose of combining nondeterminism with probability, doesn't it? At least, the idea of \"nondeterminism\" imo is that you have some information that you do not know how to quantify precisely. Maybe I misunderstood you point, though</p>",
        "id": 465986427,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724931177
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>At least in the finitely generated case, any “imprecise probability distribution” (in the sense of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.09391\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.09391</a>, i.e. a convex subset of probability space) is immediately representable in terms of upper bounds on expectations of [0,∞]-valued functions, by Minkowski-Weyl. That is, the purpose of this list of functions is to define the <em>faces</em> of the convex set. The imprecision comes from the fact that we do not know the expected values of <em>every</em> function (as Riesz-Markov would give us if we had a <em>precise</em> probability measure).</p>",
        "id": 465990491,
        "sender_full_name": "davidad (David Dalrymple)",
        "timestamp": 1724932152
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, thanks. This is more in line with the approach that uses the convex powerset monad I mentioned earlier, than trying to port what Dario and Richard did for Gaussians to the discrete case then.</p>",
        "id": 465992005,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1724932437
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277342\">Robin Piedeleu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/253118-theory.3A-categorical-probability/topic/Axiomatisation.20of.20probabilistic.20Boolean.20circuits/near/465915170\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yet another approach is the one proposed by <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"309295\">Dario Stein</span> and <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"426789\">Richard Samuelson</span> in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2204.14024\">A Category for unifying Gaussian Probability and Nondeterminism</a>. They define an <em>extended Gaussian</em> over some vector space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> as a Gaussian distribution on a quotient space of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V/D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>, where the subspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> can be thought of as a \"nondeterministic fiber\". (And, as you know, we've axiomatised this category and more in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.02284\">Graphical Quadratic Algebra</a>). </p>\n<p>The same idea could perhaps be applied in the discrete setting? We could define an extended distribution over some (finite) set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a pair of an equivalence relation over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and a distribution over its equivalence classes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For Gaussian relations, the equivalence relation is given by the quotient of a vector space by an affine subspace.  And this means that you don't have to worry about this problem involving the product vs the coproduct.  So maybe it would be easier to drop the and gate and first try to generalize this to \"discrete\" vector spaces rather than merely finite sets; ie. vector spaces over finite fields.</p>\n<p>What is really nice about Gaussian relations is that they are generated under relational composition (if represented in the right way) by the unital variance, centered normal distribution on the real line in addition to all the affine relations over the real numbers.  What is perhaps even nicer, is that one obtain Gaussian relations from affine relations via a universal construction, by freely discarding the rotations (essentially).</p>\n<p>Therefore it seems natural to ask what happens when one freely discards the \"rotations\" (if it makes sense to talk about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">O</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>q</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\sf SO}(n,\\mathbb{F}_q) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0361em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">SO</span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">q</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> ) in the category of affine relations over finite fields... or really over general fields. However, I have no idea if this uniquely determines some discrete probability distribution.</p>",
        "id": 465992990,
        "sender_full_name": "Cole Comfort",
        "timestamp": 1724932651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282874\">davidad (David Dalrymple)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/253118-theory.3A-categorical-probability/topic/Axiomatisation.20of.20probabilistic.20Boolean.20circuits/near/465990491\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>At least in the finitely generated case, any “imprecise probability distribution” (in the sense of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.09391\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.09391</a>, i.e. a convex subset of probability space) is immediately representable in terms of upper bounds on expectations…</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I’m not confident about how well this idea generalizes to infinite state spaces, and this is something I’ll be looking to encourage researchers in my ARIA programme to look into. Some particular directions of relatively well-behaved but more general-enough spaces include the Perrone-Fritz setting of tau-smooth probability measures on Top, Huot-Staton on 𝜔PAP, and whatever Goubault-Larrecq is up to here: <a href=\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3611660\">https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/3611660</a></p>",
        "id": 465993996,
        "sender_full_name": "davidad (David Dalrymple)",
        "timestamp": 1724932869
    }
